objects.question: TO AMEND H.R. 2, (1 STAT. 24, APP. 7-4-1789), FOR LAYING A DUTY ON GOODS, WARES AND MERCHANDISE IMPORTED INTO THE U.S. SO AS TO LIMIT THE DATE OF ENFORCEMENT OF THE ABOVE ACT UNTIL THE -- DAY OF -- AND FROM THENCE UNTIL THE END OF THE NEXT SESSION OF CONGRESS WHICH SHALL HAPPEN THERE AFTER.
TO PASS THE RESOLUTION THAT IT APPEARS TO THIS HOUSE, THAT THE SAID WILLIAM SMITH HAD BEEN SEVEN YEARS A CITIZEN OF THE UNITED STATES, AT THE TIME OF HIS ELECTION, AND THEREFORE ENTITLED TO HIS SEAT.

TO AMEND H.R. 8, (1 STAT. 28, APP. 7-27-1789), A BILL TO ESTABLISH AN EXECUTIVE DEPARTMENT OF FOREIGN AFFAIRS; BY PROVIDING THAT THE CHIEF CLERK WILL HAVE CHARGE OF ALL RECORDS IF THE FOREIGN AFFAIRS PRINCIPAL OFFICER IS REMOVED FROM OFFICE.
TO AMEND H.R. 8, SO AS TO ELIMINATE THE PRESIDENT'S AUTHORITY TO REMOVE A MAN FROM OFFICE.
TO PASS H.R. 8.

TO RECEDE FROM DISAGREEMENT TO CERTAIN SENATE AMENDMENTS TO H.R. 5, (1 STAT. 27, APP. 7-20-1789), A BILL FOR LAYING A DUTY OF SIX CENTS PER TON ON ALL VESSELS BUILT IN THE U.S., AND OWNED BY A CITIZEN THEREOF, AND ALL FOREIGN BUILT VESSELS NOT OWNED BY A CITIZEN.
TO PASS THE BILL (1 STAT 73, APP. 9-24-1789), TO ESTABLISH THE JUDICIAL COURTS OF THE UNITED STATES.

TO AMEND THE ACT (1 STAT 28, APP. 7-27-1789), FOR ESTABLISH- ING AN EXECUTIVE DEPARTMENT, TO BE DENOMINATED THE DEPART- MENT OF FOREIGN AFFAIRS; SO AS TO STRIKE THE WORDS "BY THE PRESIDENT", IN THE SECTION DEALING WITH THE APPOINTMENT OF A CHIEF CLERK.
TO CONCUR IN THE ACT (1 STAT 28, APP. 7-27-1789), TO ESTABLISH AN EXECUTIVE DEPARTMENT TO BE KNOWN AS THE DEPARTMENT OF FOREIGN AFFAIRS.

TO AMEND THE ACT (1 STAT 49, APP. 8-7-1789), TO ESTABLISH AN EXECUTIVE DEPARTMENT TO BE CALLED THE DEPARTMENT OF WAR; SO AS TO STRIKE "AND WHO, WHENEVER THE SAID PRINCIPAL OFFICER SHALL BE REMOVED FROM OFFICE BY THE PRESIDENT."
TO AMEND THE ACT (1 STAT 50, APP. 8-7-1789), TO PROVIDE FOR THE GOVERNMENT OF THE TERRITORY NORTHWEST OF THE OHIO RIVER; SO AS TO MAKE THE PRESIDENT'S ACTS UNDER THE BILL, SUBJECT TO SENATE APPROVAL.
TO PASS H.R. 19, (1 STAT. 70, APP. 9-22-89), A BILL FOR ALLOWING A COMPENSATION TO THE MEMBERS OF CONGRESS AND THEIR CLERKS AND OFFICERS.

TO AMEND H.R. 20, APP. 7-22-1790), A BILL TO PROVIDE FOR THE EXPENSE ATTENDING THE NEGOTIATIONS FOR TREATIES WITH INDIAN TRIBES; BY APPROPRIATING $40,000 AS A FUND TO BE USED TO NEGOTIATE SAID TREATIES. (P. 698)

TO AMEND THE ACT (1 STAT 54, APP. 8-20-1789), TO PROVIDE FOR THE EXPENSES OF NEGOTIATIONS OR TREATIES WITH THE INDIAN TRIBES, AND THE APPOINTMENT OF COMMISSIONERS; SO AS TO CHANGE THE LIMIT OF THE SUM TO BE EXPENDED IN NEGOTIATING A TREATY WITH THE INDIANS, FROM, $40,000 TO $20,000.

TO ORDER THE PREVIOUS QUESTION ON REFERRAL OF THE PROPOSED AMENDMENTS TO THE CONSTITUTION, TO A COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE, AND TO HAVE THE COMMITTEE INCORPORATE THEM IN ONE REPORT TO BE SUBMITTED TO THE HOUSE.
TO AMEND THE CONSTITUTIONAL AMENDMENTS RESOLUTION TO ADD THE WORD "EXPRESSLY" SO AS TO READ "THE POWERS NOT EXPRESSLY DELEGATED BY THE CONSTITUTION, NOR PROHIBITED TO THE STATES. ..."

TO AMEND THE CONSTITUTIONAL RESOLUTION; BY ADDING A CLAUSE PROHIBITING CONGRESS FROM INTERFERING IN THE TIMES, PLACES, OR MANNER OF HOLDING ELECTIONS OF SENATORS OR REPRESENTATIVES, EXCEPT WHEN ANY STATE SHALL REFUSE, NEGLECT OR BE UNABLE TO HOLD AN ELECTION DUE TO INVASION OR REBELLION.

TO AMEND THE CONSTITUTIONAL AMENDMENTS RESOLUTION, BY PROHIBITING CONGRESS FROM IMPOSING DIRECT TAXES, EXCEPT WHEN DUTIES COLLECTED ARE INSUFFICIENT, IN WHICH EVENT, CONGRESS MAY ASSESS EACH STATE ITS PROPORTIONATE SHARE TO DEFRAY DEFICENCY, WITH INTEREST THEREON OF 6% PER ANNUM.

TO RECEDE FROM DISAGREEMENT TO A HOUSE AMENDMENT TO THE BILL (1 STAT 65, APP. 9-2-1789), TO ESTABLISH A TREASURY DEPT.; SAID AMENDMENT PROVIDES THAT IN THE ABSENCE OF A SECRETARY OF THE TREASURY, THE ASSISTANT SHALL HAVE CHARGE OF THE OFFICE. (VICE PRESIDENT VOTING IN THE AFFIRMATIVE)
TO PASS THE RESOLUTION THAT THERE OUGHT TO BE A DISCRIMINA- TION BETWEEN THE COMPENSATION ALLOWED TO SENATORS AND TO REPRESENTATIVES.

TO AMEND THE ACT (1 STAT 70, APP. 9-22-89), TO ALLOW COMPENSATION TO THE MEMBERS OF CONGRESS AND TO THE OFFICERS OF BOTH HOUSES, SO AS TO REDUCE THE COMPENSATION FOR REPRESENTATIVES FROM SIX TO FIVE DOLLARS.
TO AMEND THE COMPENSATION BILL TO REDUCE THE COMPENSATION TO THE SENATORS FROM SIX DOLLARS TO FIVE.
TO PASS H.R. 21, (1 STAT. 70, APP. 9-11-1789), TO ESTABLISH THE SALARIES OF EXECUTIVE OFFICERS AND THEIR ASSISTANTS AND CLERKS. (P. 796)

TO AMEND THE HOUSE RESOLUTION TO PROPOSE CERTAIN ARTICLES TO THE LEGISLATURES OF THE STATES AS AMENDMENTS TO THE CONSTITUTION; SO AS TO AMEND THE FIRST CLAUSE TO STATE "AFTER THE FIRST ENUMERATION REQUIRED BY THE FIRST ARTICLE OF THE CONSTITUTION, THERE SHALL BE ONE REPRESENTATIVE FOR EVERY 30,000 UNTIL THE NUMBER SHALL AMOUNT TO TWO HUNDRED."
TO AMEND THE CONSTITUTIONAL AMENDMENT RESOLUTION TO ADD TO THE FOURTH ARTICLE, AFTER THE WORDS "COMMON GOOD", THE WORDS "TO INSTRUCT THEIR REPRESENTATIVES."

TO AMEND THE CONSTITUTIONAL AMENDMENT RESOLUTION TO ADD TO THE 5TH ARTICLE THE PROVISION THAT THE MILITARY SHOULD BE UNDER STRICT SUBORDINATION TO AND GOVERNED BY THE CIVIL POWER, ALSO THAT NO TROOPS SHALL BE RAISED DURING PEACE TIME WITHOUT CONSENT OF 2/3RDS OF THE MEMBERS OF CONGRESS, AND THAT NO SOLDIERS SHALL BE ENLISTED FOR LONGER THAN THE DURATION OF THE WAR.
TO INSIST ON THE SENATE AMENDMENT TO THE COMPENSATION BILL, THAT NO SENATOR SHALL RECEIVE MORE THAN $6.00 PER DAY FROM THE END OF ONE SESSION TO THE NEXT.

TO AMEND THE RESOLUTION TO FIX THE PLACE FOR THE PERMAMENT SEAT OF THE GOVERNMENT, BY ESTABLISHING "THE NORTH BANK OF THE POTOMAC RIVER, IN THE STATE OF MARYLAND", AS THE NEW SEAT OF GOVERNMENT. (P. 881)
TO AMEND THE SEAT OF GOVERNMENT RESOLUTION TO ESTABLISH WILMINGTON, DELAWARE AS THE NEW SEAT OF GOVERNMENT.
TO AMEND THE SEAT OF GOVERNMENT RESOLUTION TO READ "THAT THE PERMANENT SEAT OF THE GOVERNMENT OUGHT TO BE --- ON THE POTOMAC, SUSQUEHANNAH, OR DELAWARE RIVERS.
TO AMEND THE SEAT OF GOVERNMENT RESOLUTION, BY PROVIDING TO LOCATE THE CAPITOL ON THE BANKS OF THE DELAWARE RIVER.
TO AMEND THE SEAT OF GOVERNMENT RESOLUTION TO STRIKE "EAST BANK" AND INSERT "BANKS ON EITHER SIDE OF THE RIVER SUSQUEHANNAH IN PENNSYLVANIA."
TO AMEND THE SEAT OF GOVERNMENT RESOLUTION TO INCLUDE MARYLAND IN THE LIST OF PROPOSED SITES FOR THE SEAT OF GOVERNMENT.
TO AMEND THE SEAT OF GOVERNMENT RESOLUTION; TO MOVE THE TEMPORARY SEAT TO WILMINGTON, DELAWARE, RATHER THAN NEW YORK CITY.
TO AMEND THE SEAT OF GOVERNMENT RESOLUTION, TO MOVE THE TEMPORARY SEAT TO PHILADELPHIA, INSTEAD OF NEW YORK.

TO AMEND THE SEAT OF GOVERNMENT RESOLUTION TO PROVIDE THAT BEFORE A SITE IS PURCHASED FOR A BUILDING, THE STATES OF MARYLAND AND PENNSYLVANIA MUST REMOVE ALL OBSTRUCTIONS TO THE NAVIGATION OF THE SUSQUEHANNA RIVER BETWEEN THE SITE SELECTED AND THE MOUTH OF THE RIVER. (P. 886)
TO AMEND THE SEAT OF GOVERNMENT RESOLUTION, TO AUTHORIZE THE PRESIDENT TO APPOINT THREE COMMISSIONERS TO SELECT A SITE, WITH CERTAIN STIPULATIONS.
TO RECONSIDER AN AMENDMENT TO THE CONSTITUTIONAL AMENDMENT RESOLUTION, TO RESTORE CERTAIN WORDS TO THE TENTH ARTICLE REGARDING TRIALS OF NAVAL CREWS.
TO RECEDE FROM DISAGREEMENT TO THE SENATE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 19; SAID AMENDMENT PROVIDES "THAT THIS ACT SHALL CONTINUE IN FORCE UNTIL THE FOURTH DAY OF MARCH 1796."
TO RECONSIDER THE VOTE ON A SENATE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 19, CONCERNING TERMINATION OF THE ACT AND FIXING OF SALARIES. (P. 890)
TO AGREE TO THE SENATE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 19, TO TERMINATE THE ACT ON MARCH 4, 1796. (P. 892)
TO AMEND S. 1, AN ACT TO ESTABLISH THE JUDICIAL COURTS OF THE U.S.; BY PROVIDING TO ESTABLISH A COURT IN CHESTERTOWN, RATHER THAN EASTOWN.

TO AMEND THE ACT (1 STAT 101, APP. 3-1-90), TO ALLOW COMPEN- SATION TO THE JUDGES OF THE SUPREME COURT AND OTHER COURTS, AND TO THE ATTORNEY GENERAL; TO INCREASE THE SALARY OF THE CHIEF JUSTICE FROM $3500 TO $4000. (VICE PRESIDENT VOTING IN THE AFFIRMATIVE)
TO PASS H.R. 25, (1 STAT. 130, APP. 7-16-1790), TO ESTABLISH A SEAT OF GOVERNMENT OF THE UNITED STATES ON THE SUSQUEHANNA RIVER IN PENNSYLVANIA.
TO AMEND H.R. 25, (1 STAT 130, APP. 7-16-1790), TO ESTABLISH THE SEAT OF THE U.S. GOVERNMENT; SO AS TO ELIMINATE PA., AS A SITE FOR A PERMANENT SEAT OF GOVERNMENT.
TO AMEND H.R. 25, TO ELIMINATE THE "BANKS OF THE SUSQUEHANNA RIVER IN PENNSYLVANIA" AS A SITE FOR THE SEAT OF GOVERNMENT.
TO AMEND H.R. 25, TO INSERT, AS POSSIBLE SITES, CERTAIN COUNTIES IN THE STATE OF PENNSYLVANIA, INCLUDING GERMANTOWN AND PHILADELPHIA. (VICE PRESIDENT VOTING IN THE AFFIRMATIVE)
TO AGREE TO THE SENATE AMENDMENT TO THE CONSTITUTIONAL AMENDMENT RESOLUTION, WHICH WOULD ALTER THE 8TH ARTICLE. (P. 913)

TO AMEND S. 4, (1 STAT. 93, APP. 9-29-1789), A BILL FOR REGULATING PROCESSES IN THE COURTS OF THE U.S.; SO AS TO PROVIDE THAT WRITS OR PROCESSES ISSUED OUT OF THE COURTS SHALL BE ISSUED IN THE NAME OF THE U.S., NOT IN THE NAME OF THE PRESIDENT. (P. 914)
TO AMEND H.R. 25, TO STRIKE "AND THAT UNTIL THE NECESSARY BUILDINGS SHALL BE ERECTED THEREIN, THE SEAT OF THE GOVERNMENT SHALL CONTINUE AT THE CITY OF NEW YORK."
TO ADHERE TO THE AMENDMENT TO S. 4, WHICH WOULD PROVIDE THAT WRITS AND PROCESSES SHALL BE ISSUED IN THE NAME OF THE U.S. RATHER THAN IN THE NAME OF THE PRESIDENT. (P. 916)
TO PASS H.R. 25.
TO POSTPONE CONSIDERATION OF AN AMENDMENT. TO H.R. 25. (P. 924)

TO AMEND H.R. 25 SO AS TO PROVIDE THAT IF CONGRESS ACCEPTED THE DISTRICTS CEDED BY STATE OF PA., FOR A SEAT OF GOVERNMENT, THE DISTRICT SHALL BE GOVERNED BY THE LAWS OF PA., UNTIL CONGRESS SHALL OTHERWISE PROVIDE BY LAW. (P. 926)
TO RECEDE FROM THE HOUSE AMENDMENT TO S. 4, WHICH ELIMINATES THE NAME OF THE PRESIDENT FROM WRITS OR PROCESSES ISSUED FROM COURTS. (SPEAKER VOTING IN THE AFFIRMATIVE.)

TO DISAGREE TO THE SENATE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 27, TO ADOPT TO THE CONSTITUTION THE ESTABLISHMENT OF THE TROOPS RAISED UNDER RESOLVES OF THE OLD CONGRESS, WITH AMENDMENTS; SAID AMENDMENT WOULD AMEND THE CONSTITUTION BY EMPOWERING THE PRESIDENT TO CALL OUT THE MILITIA GENERALLY FOR THE PROTECT- ION OF THE FRONTIERS AGAINST INVASION BY HOSTILE INDIANS.
TO AGREE TO THE COMMITTEE REPORT THAT UNFINISHED BUSINESS BETWEEN THE TWO HOUSES AT THE LAST ADJOURNMENT, OUGHT TO BE REGARDED AS IF IT HAD NOT BEEN PASSED UPON BY EITHER HOUSE.
TO REFER TO A COMMITTEE THE MEMORIAL TO THE SENATE AND HOUSE, FOR THE ABOLITION OF SLAVERY.
TO INSERT IN THE JOURNAL, THE REPORT OF THE SPECIAL COMMITTEE AND THE REPORT OF THE COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE HOUSE WITH AMENDMENTS, REGARDING THE MEMORIALS TO ABOLISH SLAVERY.
TO RESOLVE INTO A COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE HOUSE ON THE REPORT OF THE SECRETARY OF THE TREASURY RELATIVE TO THE SUPPORT OF THE PUBLIC CREDIT. (P. 1530)
TO DISCHARGE THE COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE FROM THAT PART OF THE REPORT OF THE SECRETARY OF THE TREASURY RELATING TO AN ASSUMPTION OF THE STATE DEBTS.

TO AMEND H.R. 60, A BILL TO ADJUST AND SATISFY THE CLAIMS TO BARON FREDERICK WILLIAM DE STEUBEN; TO STRIKE THE PROVISION TO INDEMNIFY BARON DE STEUBEN FOR HIS SACRIFICES AND EXPENSES IN COMING TO THE U.S. FOR HIS SERVICES DURING THE LATE WAR WITH AN ANNUAL COMPENSATION AND 1000 ACRES OF LAND.

TO AMEND H.R. 60, TO PROVIDE TO INDEMNIFY BARON STEUBEN FOR HIS SACRIFICES AND EXPENSES IN COMING TO THE U.S. FOR HIS SERVICES DURING THE LATE WAR, $2706 ANNUAL TO COMMENCE ON OCT. 1ST. 1777. (P. 1556)
TO PASS H.R. 60, AS AMENDED. (P. 1557)

TO ORDER A THIRD READING FOR THE BILL TO PREVENT BRINGING GOODS, WARES AND MERCHANDISE FROM THE STATE OF RHODE ISLAND AND PROVIDENCE PLANTATIONS, INTO THE U.S., AND TO AUTHORIZE A DEMAND OF MONEY FROM THAT STATE.
TO PASS THE BILL TO PREVENT BRINGING GOODS, WARES, AND MERCHANDISE FROM RHODE ISLAND AND PROVIDENCE PLANTATIONS, INTO THE U.S., AND TO AUTHORIZE A DEMAND OF MONEY FROM THAT STATE.

TO ADOPT THE HOUSE RESOLUTION TO DIRECT THE SECRETARY OF THE TREASURY TO LIQUIDATE ARREARAGES OF PAY DUE CERTAIN NON-COMMISSIONED OFFICERS AND SOLDIERS; PAYMENT TO BE MADE WHEN CERTAIN CONDITIONS ARE MET.
TO AGREE TO AN AMENDMENT TO THE HOUSE RESOLUTION CONCERNING ARREARAGES OF PAY DUE CERTAIN NON-COMMISSIONED OFFICERS AND SOLDIERS; AMENDMENT CONCERNING POWERS OF ATTORNEY OBTAINED BY FORGERY OR FRAUD.
TO AGREE TO THE COMMITTEE REPORT WHICH RECOMMENDS GRANTING AN ANNUITY TO BARON DE STEUBEN.
TO DECIDE IF THE SUM OF TWO THOUSAND DOLLARS WILL REMAIN IN THE ACT (6 STAT 2, APP. 6-4-90), TO ADJUST THE CLAIM OF BARON DE STEUBEN. (VICE PRESIDENT VOTING IN THE AFFIRMATIVE.)
TO AMEND THE STEUBEN BILL TO ELIMINATE THE PROVISION FOR A SUM OF $7000, IN ADDITION TO THE MONEY ALREADY RECEIVED BY HIM. (VICE PRESIDENT VOTING IN THE NEGATIVE)

TO AMEND H.R. 63, MAKING PROVISIONS FOR THE UNITED STATES DEBT; TO ISSUE CERTIFICATES FOR THE BILLS OF CREDIT ISSUED BY THE AUTHORITY OF CONGRESS ASSEMBLED. (P. 1619) DOLLARS IN THOSE BILLS FOR $1 IN SPECIE. (P. 1619)
TO AMEND H.R. 63, A BILL TO MAKE PROVISIONS FOR THE U.S. DEBT; BY ADDING THAT INTEREST SHOULD BE COMPUTED ON THE SAID BILLS FROM A CERTAIN DATE.
TO AMEND THE STEUBEN BILL TO CHANGE TO $2500, THE SUM TO BE PAID DE STEUBEN. (VICE PRESIDENT VOTING IN THE AFFIRMATIVE)

TO CONCUR IN THE SENATE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 35, AN ACT PROVID- ING THE MEANS OF INTERCOURSE BETWEEN THE U.S. AND FOREIGN NATIONS; SAID AMENDMENT WOULD ELIMINATE THE CLAUSES WHICH SPECIFY THE OFFICERS TO BE EMPLOYED ABROAD AND THE SALARIES OF EACH, AND (FOR THE PRESIDENT TO APPLY THE SUM TO BE APPROPRIATED.)

TO CONCUR IN THE SENATE'S AMENDMENT TO H.R. 60; TO INDEMNIFY BARON STEUBEN FOR HIS SACRIFICE AND EXPENSES IN COMING TO THE U.S. FOR HIS SERVICES IN THE LATE WAR, AN ANNUITY OF $2,500 DURING HIS LIFE TO COMMENCE ON JAN. 1, 1790.
TO RECEDE FROM DISAGREEMENT TO THE SENATE AMENDMENT TO H.R. 35, AN ACT PROVIDING THE MEANS OF INTERCOURSE BETWEEN THE U.S. AND FOREIGN NATIONS.
TO CONSIDER THE RESOLUTION PERTAINING TO HOLDING THE NEXT SESSION OF CONGRESS IN PHILADELPHIA. (P. 1623)
TO SUSTAIN THE DECISION OF THE CHAIR CONCERNING AN AMENDMENT TO THE RESOLUTION CONCERNING THE MEETING PLACE OF THE NEXT SESSION OF CONGRESS.
TO AMEND THE RESOLUTION TO PROVIDE TO HOLD THE NEXT SESSION OF CONGRESS IN NEW YORK CITY. (P. 1625)
TO AMEND THE RESOLUTION TO PROVIDE TO HOLD THE NEXT SESSION OF CONGRESS IN PHILADELPHIA OR BALTIMORE.
TO AMEND THE RESOLUTION TO PROVIDE THAT CONGRESS WILL HOLD THEIR NEXT SESSION AT PHILADELPHIA.
TO CONCUR IN THE HOUSE RESOLUTION THAT CONGRESS SHALL MEET AND HOLD THEIR NEXT SESSION AT THE CITY OF PHILADELPHIA.
TO DECIDE IF IT BE EXPEDIENT, AT THIS TIME TO DETERMINE UPON ANY PLACE FOR THE PERMANENT SEAT OF THE GOVERNMENT. (VICE PRESIDENT VOTING IN THE NEGATIVE.)
TO AMEND THE BILL TO DETERMINE THE PERMANENT SEAT OF CONGRESS AND THE U.S. GOVERNMENT; TO INSERT "THE EASTERLY BANK OF THE POTOMAC", AS A SITE FOR THE GOVERNMENT.
TO AMEND THE GOVERNMENT SEAT BILL; TO INSERT BALTIMORE AS A SITE FOR CONGRESS. (P. 986)
TO CONSIDER THE RESOLUTION TO PICK THE PERMANENT AND TEMPORARY SEATS OF GOVERNMENT.
TO COMMIT THE SECOND SEAT OF GOVERNMENT RESOLUTION TO THE COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE.
TO RESOLVE INTO THE COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE IN ORDER TO CONSIDER H.R. 62, TO REPEAL IMPORT DUTIES AND TAXES ON DISTILLED SPIRITS, AND TO LAY OTHERS IN THEIR STEAD.
TO AMEND THE SECOND SEAT OF GOVERNMENT RESOLUTION TO CHANGE THE SITE FOR THE NEXT SESSION OF CONGRESS FROM PHILADELPHIA TO BALTIMORE.
TO PASS THE SECOND SEAT OF GOVERNMENT RESOLUTION AS AMENDED.
TO POSTPONE, FOR TWO WEEKS, CONSIDERATION OF THE HOUSE RESOLUTION TO HOLD THE NEXT SESSION OF CONGRESS IN THE TOWN OF BALTIMORE. (P. 989)
TO CONSIDER THE REPORT OF THE COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE, CONCERNING H.R. 62.
TO AMEND H.R. 62, BY ELIMINATING THE TWO SECTIONS WHICH PROVIDE FOR AN EXCISE TAX ON ALL SPIRITS DISTILLED IN THE U.S. (P. 1642)

TO AMEND H.R. 178, (1 STAT 138, APP. 8-4-1790), TO MAKE PROVISIONS FOR THE DEBTS OF THE U.S., SO AS TO PROVIDE TO DISCHARGE THE ALTERNATIVES PROPOSED IN THE BILL AND TO FUND THE DOMESTIC DEBT OF THE GOVERNMENT AT AN INTEREST OF 4% PER ANNUM.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT OF H.R. 62. (P. 1644)

TO AMEND H.R. 69, RELATING TO ACCOUNTS BETWEEN THE U.S., AND THE INDIVIDUAL STATES; TO ELIMINATE THE CLAUSE WHICH PROVIDES THAT THE RULE FOR APPORTIONING THE EXPENSES OF THE WAR, SHALL BE THE SAME AS THAT WHICH IS PRESCRIBED BY THE CONSTITUTION FOR THE APPORTIONMENT OF REPRESENTATION AND DIRECT TAXES.

TO AMEND H.R. 65, A BILL TO REGULATE INTERCOURSE WITH THE INDIAN TRIBES; BY ELIMINATING THE SECION WHICH PROVIDES THAT A CONGRESSIONAL APPROPRIATION BE LAID OUT IN GOODS AND ARTICLES OF TRADE SUITABLE FOR SUPPLYING THE WANTS AND NEEDS OF THE INDIANS, AND TO BE RETAILED TO THEM THROUGH THE VARIOUS INDIAN AGENCIES.

TO AMEND THE HOUSE BILL (1 STAT 129, APP. 7-5-90), TO AUTHORIZE THE PURCHASE OF WEST POINT; SO AS TO PROVIDE THAT THE PRESIDENT CAUSE TO BE PURCHASED, THAT TRACT OF LAND IN NEW YORK, CALLED WEST POINT.
TO PASS THE HOUSE BILL (1 STAT 129, APP. 7-5-90), TO AUTHORIZE THE PURCHASE OF WEST POINT. (P. 994)
